            <section class="artwork-details" vid="28">
                <div class="detail-col" vid="29">
                    <h3 vid="30">Concept</h3>
                    <div class="detail-body" vid="31">
                        This monolithic structure serves as a dialogue between the stone masonry of the Mutapa Empire and the industrial rigidity of the modern era. By reinterpreting the iconic chevron patterns of the Great Enclosure through laser-cut Corten steel, the work interrogates the persistence of ancestral memory within the "rust-belt" aesthetics of contemporary life. It is an altar to the continuity of form across centuries of displacement.
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="detail-col" vid="32">
                    <h3 vid="33">Material Process</h3>
                    <div class="detail-body" vid="34">
                        Fabricated from 12mm weather-resistant structural steel, the piece underwent a controlled oxidation process over eighteen months. The surface was treated with a proprietary saline solution to accelerate the development of the hematite patina, mirroring the natural weathering of iron-rich ores found in the Mashonaland plateau. Every seam is hand-welded using archival slag-rich techniques to emphasize the raw industrial labor.
                    </div>
                </div>

